http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Sun 20 Mar 2016
Source: OIE, WAHID weekly disease information 2016; 29(12) [edited]
http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapFullEventReport&reportid=19942


Foot and mouth disease, Korea (Rep of)
--------------------------------------
Information received on [and dated] 20 Mar 2016 from Dr Oh Soon-Min, director - chief veterinary officer, General Animal Health Division, Ministry of Agriculture, Food and Rural Affairs (MAFRA), SEJONG-SI, Korea (Rep of)

Summary
Report type: follow-up report no 3
Date of start of the event: 11 Jan 2016
Date of confirmation of the event: 12 Jan 2016
Reason for notification: reoccurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: 22 May 2015
Manifestation of disease: clinical disease
Causal agent: foot and mouth disease virus
Serotype: O
Nature of diagnosis: clinical, Laboratory (basic), Laboratory (advanced)
This event pertains to the whole country.

[The report includes details of 10 new outbreaks in various locations in the province Chungcheongnam-Do, which started during the 1st half of March 2016. For their respective detailed dates, locations and statistics, and for an interactive map, please go to the source URL].

Total outbreaks: 10
Total animals affected
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Swine / 13 200 / 57 / 0 / 10 575 / 0

Outbreak statistics [rates apparent, expressed as percentages]:
Species / Morbidity rate / Mortality rate / Case fatality rate / Proportion susceptible animals lost*
Swine / 0.43 / 0.00 / 0.00 / 80
*Removed from the susceptible population through death, destruction and/or slaughter

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: unknown or inconclusive
Epidemiological comments: epidemiological survey is currently being implemented. Infected animals were destroyed.

Control measures
Measures applied: movement control inside the country, screening, vaccination in response to the outbreak, (s), disinfection/disinfestation, quarantines, stamping out, control of wildlife reservoirs, zoning, no treatment of affected animals

Measures to be applied: no other measures

Diagnostic test results:

Laboratory name and type: Animal and Plant Quarantine Agency (National laboratory)

Species / Test / Test date / Result
Swine / real-time reverse transcriptase/polymerase chain reaction (RRT-PCR) / 24 Feb 2016 / Positive
Swine / RRT-PCR / 8 Mar 2016 / Positive
Swine / RRT-PCR / 15 Mar 2016 / Positive
Swine / reverse transcription/polymerase chain reaction (RT-PCR) / 10 Mar 2016 / Positive
Swine / RT-PCR / 12 Mar 2016 / Positive

Future reporting
The event is continuing. Weekly follow-up reports will be submitted.

The location of the outbreak can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The current FMFV-O event recurred in South Korea about 6 months after the notification on the previous wave, apparently caused by the same virus strain, as resolved. The current follow-up report is indicative of the disease spreading northwards.

See the event summary and map at http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review/viewsummary?reportid=16695.

The summarized statistics of the current event, which reportedly started on 11 Jan 2016, as of 20 Mar 2016, are as follows:

Outbreak summary:
Total outbreaks = 14 (Submitted)
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Swine / 27 186 / 192 / 0 / 24 561 / 0

The above data are derived from OIE's WAHID archive at http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/temp/reports/en_fup_0000019942_20160321_181345.pdf
This web-page includes a map showing all 14 reported outbreaks.

In the past, scarce information obtained from North Korea obscured FMD activity there during the events in S Korea. One wonders about the actual FMD situation at present in N Korea. - Mod.AS

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4114053,195.]
